ce:section.ce:para:
Fig. 3
 displays the UV–visible absorption spectrum of RA-AuNPs, exhibiting SPR absorption band (468 – 694 nm), λmax 534 nm for RA-AuNPs. After the addition of 21 amino acids (alanine, aspartic acid, glutamic acid, phenylalanine, threonine, leucine, valine, glutamine, cysteine, glycine, isoleucine, methionine, serine, histidine hydrochloride, tryptophan, asparagine, proline, arginine hydrochloride, hydroxyproline, lysine, tyrosine. 1.0 mM), the solution of RA-AuNPs with Cys displays complete disappearance of SPR absorption band at 534 nm in the absorption spectrum and appearance of a new SPR absorption band at 606 nm. Interestingly, remaining amino acids did not show any significant changes on the SPR absorption spectrum of RA-AuNPs, suggesting the RA-AuNPs act as visual reader for detection of Cys. To enhance the utility of RA-AuNPs as a colorimetric probe, different metal ions solutions (Mg2+, Ca2+, Fe2+, Fe3+, Co2+, Ni2+, Hg2+, Pb2+, Mn2+, Zn2+, Cu2+ and Cr3+, 1.0 mM) were treated independently with RA-AuNPs solution and measured the corresponding absorption spectra (Fig. 4
). Only Hg2+ ion shows the intensity of characteristic SPR band of RA-AuNPs is blue-shifted to 506 nm with increasing absorbance values and the color of the solution is unchanged, whereas other metal ions did not influence on the SPR absorption band of RA-AuNPs. Hence, the RA-AuNPs could be used as sensor for both Cys and Hg2+ detection by measuring the changes in SPR absorption band of RA-AuNPs.
